Memini (a present- perfect, meaning properly ‘ I have taken to my mind,' ‘ I bear in memory') takes a pres. inf. or a perf. inf. : in the former case it is implied that the subject was an eye—witness of the fact which he remembers. In the latter case this may be so, but is not of necessity implied. The pres. inf. implies the continuance of the action up to the time when it was ‘taken into the mind.'
